{{Infobox language | name = Duit | nativename = | map = Chibcha lang.png | mapcaption = The second-most southern yellow dot indicates roughly the area where Duit was spoken | states = [[Boyacá Department|Boyacá]], [[Colombia]] | region = [[Altiplano Cundiboyacense]] | ethnicity = [[Muisca people|Muisca]] | nation = [[Muisca Confederation]] | extinct = yes | speakers = 0 | familycolor = American | fam1 = [[Chibcha language|Chibcha]] | fam2 = Kuna-Colombian | fam3 = Muysccubun | script = Only [[Muisca numerals|numerals]] | iso3 = none | linglist = qrx | lingname = (also used for the unrelated ''Mittlere Neu-Hebriden'') | glotto = duit1239 | glottorefname = Duit }}
'''Duit''' is an extinct [[Chibcha language]], spoken by the [[Muisca people|Muisca]] of present-day [[Boyacá Department|Boyacá]], [[Colombia]]. The language appears in the modern name of the pre-Columbian settlement and last ruler [[Tundama]]; [[Duitama]].<ref name=PueblosTundama>{{es}} [http://pueblosoriginarios.com/biografias/tundama.html Biography Cacique Tundama] - Pueblos Originarios</ref>
== Description == The language is only known from one fragment analysed by [[List of Muisca scholars|scholar]] [[Ezequiel Uricoechea]] in 1871. The linguist mentioned that the analysed text was part of a larger work that hitherto has not been found. From the short text it was clear that the Duit language differed slightly from the main version of Chibcha, Muysccubun, spoken by the Muisca on the [[Altiplano Cundiboyacense]].<ref>{{cite LSA |last=[[Ezequiel Uricoechea|Uricoechea]] |first=Ezequiel |year=1871 |title=Gramática, vocabulario, catecismo y confesionario de la lengua chibcha, según antiguos manuscritos anónimos e inéditos}}</ref>
As the Muisca did not have a script, only for their [[Muisca numerals|numerals]], written Duit language texts do not exist.<ref>Izquierdo Peña, 2009</ref>
