=== Evidence from phonetic series ===
[[File:Shuowen-Shuo.png|thumb|upright=0.9|alt=page of a Chinese dictionary, with headings in seal script and entries in conventional script|Page from a copy of a [[Song dynasty]] edition of the ''[[Shuowen Jiezi]]'', an early source on the structure of characters, showing characters with the {{lang|zh-Hant|言}} element]]
Although the Chinese writing system is not alphabetic, comparison of words whose characters share a phonetic element (a phonetic series) yields much information about pronunciation.
Often the characters in a phonetic series are still pronounced alike, as in the character {{lang|zh-Hant|中}} (''zhōng'', 'middle'), which was adapted to write the words ''chōng'' ('pour', {{lang|zh-Hant|沖}}) and ''zhōng'' ('loyal', {{lang|zh-Hant|忠}}).<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 1007a,p,k.</ref>
In other cases the words in a phonetic series have very different sounds in any known variety of Chinese, but are assumed to have been similar at the time the characters were chosen.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=43–44}}

A key principle, first proposed by the Swedish sinologist [[Bernhard Karlgren]], holds that the initials of words written with the same phonetic component had a common [[point of articulation]] in Old Chinese.
For example, since Middle Chinese dentals and retroflex stops occur together in phonetic series, they are traced to a single Old Chinese dental series, with the retroflex stops conditioned by an Old Chinese medial {{IPA|*-r-}}.
The Middle Chinese dental sibilants and retroflex sibilants also occur interchangeably in phonetic series, and are similarly traced to a single Old Chinese sibilant series, with the retroflex sibilants conditioned by the Old Chinese medial {{IPA|*-r-}}.{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=228–232}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=191–196, 203–206}}{{efn|In 1940, Karlgren published the first complete reconstruction of Old Chinese in a dictionary called the ''Grammata Serica'', in which characters are arranged by phonetic series within rhyme groups.
The 1957 revision ''[[Grammata Serica Recensa]]'' (GSR) remains a standard reference, even though Karlgren's reconstructions have been superseded by the work of later scholars such as [[Wang Li (linguist)|Wang Li]], [[Edwin G. Pulleyblank|E. G. Pulleyblank]], [[Li Fang-Kuei]] and [[William H. Baxter|William Baxter]].{{sfnp|Schuessler|2009|p=ix}}}}

However, there are several cases where quite different Middle Chinese initials appear together in a phonetic series.
Karlgren and subsequent workers have proposed either additional Old Chinese consonants or initial consonant clusters in such cases.
For example, the Middle Chinese palatal sibilants appear in two distinct kinds of series, with dentals and with velars:{{efn|Middle Chinese forms are given in [[Karlgren–Li reconstruction of Middle Chinese|Li Fang-Kuei's revision of Karlgren's notation]],{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=224–227}} with minor simplifications suggested by {{harvp|Coblin|1986|p=9}}.}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|周}} ''tśjəu'' (< {{IPA|*tj-}}) 'cycle; Zhou dynasty', {{lang|zh-Hant|彫}} ''tieu'' (< {{IPA|*t-}}) 'carve' and {{lang|zh-Hant|調}} ''dieu'' (< {{IPA|*d-}}) 'adjust'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 1083a,p,x.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=192–193}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|制}} ''tśjäi-'' (< {{IPA|*kj-}}) 'cut out' and {{lang|zh-Hant|猘}} ''kjäi-'' (< {{IPA|*krj-}}) 'mad dog'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 335a,5.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=211}}
It is believed that the palatals arose from dentals and velars followed by an Old Chinese medial {{IPA|*-j-}}, unless the medial {{IPA|*-r-}} was also present.
While all such dentals were palatalized, the conditions for palatalization of velars are only partly understood (see [[#Medials|Medials]] below).{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=193–194, 210–214, 569–570}}

Similarly, it is proposed that the {{IPA|*-r-}} medial could occur after labials and velars, complementing the instances proposed as sources of Middle Chinese retroflex dentals and sibilants, to account for such connections as:{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=240–241}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=199–202}}{{efn|Karlgren originally postulated Old Chinese consonant clusters with {{IPA|*-l-}} in such cases.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1962a|pp=110–111}}}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|筆}} ''pjet'' (< {{IPA|*pr-}}) 'writing pencil' and {{lang|zh-Hant|律}} ''ljwet'' (< {{IPA|*br-}}) 'law; rule'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 502d,c.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=280, 775}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|監}} ''kam'' (< {{IPA|*kr-}}) 'look at' and {{lang|zh-Hant|藍}} ''lâm'' (< {{IPA|*ɡr-}}) 'indigo'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 609a,k.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=201}}
Thus the Middle Chinese lateral ''l-'' is believed to reflect Old Chinese {{IPA|*-r-}}.
Old Chinese voiced and voiceless laterals {{IPA|*l-}} and {{IPA|*l̥-}} are proposed to account for a different group of series such as
* {{lang|zh-Hant|脫}} ''dwât'' (< {{IPA|*l-}}) and ''thwât'' (< {{IPA|*l̥-}}) 'peel off', {{lang|zh-Hant|悅}} ''jwät'' (< {{IPA|*lj-}}) 'pleased' and {{lang|zh-Hant|說}} ''śjwät'' (< OC {{IPA|*l̥j-}}) 'speak'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 324a,o,m,q.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=197}}{{efn|Originally proposed as voiced and voiceless fricative initials in {{harvp|Pulleyblank|1962a|pp=114–119}}.}}
This treatment of the Old Chinese liquids is further supported by Tibeto-Burman cognates and by transcription evidence.
For example, the name of the city [[Alexandria Eschate|Alexandria]] was transcribed in the ''[[Book of Han]]'' as ⟨{{lang|zh-Hant|烏弋山離}}⟩, which is reconstructed as {{IPA|*ʔa-ljək-srjan-rjaj}}.{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|2000|p=15}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=795, 802, 785, 773}}
Traces of the earlier liquids are also found in the divergent [[Waxiang dialect]] of western [[Hunan]].{{sfnp|Baxter|Sagart|2014|pp=109–110}}

Voiceless nasal initials {{IPA|*m̥-}}, {{IPA|*n̥-}} and {{IPA|*ŋ̊-}} are proposed (following [[Dong Tonghe]] and [[Edwin Pulleyblank]]) in series such as:{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1962a|p=92}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|墨}} ''mək'' 'ink' and {{lang|zh-Hant|黑}} ''xək'' (< {{IPA|*m̥-}}) 'black'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 904c,a.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=189}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|難}} ''nân'' 'difficult' and {{lang|zh-Hant|灘}} ''thân'' (< {{IPA|*n̥-}}) 'foreshore'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 152d,m.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=193}}
* {{lang|zh-Hant|虐}} ''ngjak'' 'cruel' and {{lang|zh-Hant|謔}} ''xjak'' (< {{IPA|*ŋ̊-}}) 'to ridicule'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 1118a,d.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=208}}

Clusters {{IPA|*sn-}} and so on are proposed (following Karlgren) for alternations of Middle Chinese nasals and ''s-'' such as
* {{lang|zh-Hant|如}} ''ńźjwo'' (< {{IPA|*nj-}}) 'resemble' and {{lang|zh-Hant|絮}} ''sjwo-'' (< {{IPA|*snj-}}) 'raw silk'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 94g,u.</ref>{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=222}}
Other cluster initials, including {{IPA|*s}} with stops or stops with {{IPA|*l}}, have been suggested but their existence and nature remains an open question.{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=241–243}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=227–234}}

=== Back initials ===
The [[Song dynasty]] rhyme tables classified ''Qieyun'' syllables as either "open" ({{lang|zh-Hant|開}} ''kāi'') or "closed" ({{lang|zh-Hant|合}} ''hé''), with the latter believed to indicate a medial ''-w-'' or lip rounding.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=32}}
This medial was unevenly distributed, being distinctive only after velar and laryngeal initials or before ''-ai'', ''-an'' or ''-at''.
This is taken (following [[André-Georges Haudricourt]] and [[Sergei Yakhontov]]) to indicate that Old Chinese had [[labialised velar|labiovelar]] and labiolaryngeal initials but no labiovelar medial.{{sfnp|Haudricourt|1954b|p=359}}
The remaining occurrences of Middle Chinese ''-w-'' are believed to result from [[vowel breaking|breaking]] of a back vowel before these codas (see [[#Vowels|Vowels]] below).{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=233–234}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=180}}

As Middle Chinese ''g-'' occurs only in palatal environments, Li attempted to derive both ''g-'' and ''ɣ-'' from Old Chinese {{IPA|*ɡ-}}, but had to assume irregular developments in some cases.  [[Li Rong (linguist)|Li Rong]] showed that several words with Middle Chinese initial ''ɣ-'' were distinguished in modern [[Min Chinese|Min]] dialects.  For example, {{lang|zh-Hant|厚}} 'thick' and {{lang|zh-Hant|後}} 'after' were both ''ɣəu:'' in Middle Chinese, but have velar and zero initials respectively in several Min dialects.  Most authors now assume both {{IPA|*ɡ-}} and {{IPA|*ɦ-}}, with subsequent lenition of {{IPA|*ɡ-}} in non-palatal environments.  Similarly {{IPA|*w-}} is assumed as the labialized counterpart of {{IPA|*ɦ-}}.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=209–210}}{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|2000|pp=13–14}}<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 114a, 115a.</ref>

[[Pan Wuyun]] has proposed a revision of the above scheme to account for the fact that Middle Chinese glottal stop and laryngeal fricatives occurred together in phonetic series, unlike dental stops and fricatives, which were usually separated.
Instead of the glottal stop initial {{IPA|*ʔ-}} and fricatives {{IPA|*h-}} and {{IPA|*ɦ-}}, he proposed [[uvular stop]]s {{IPA|*q-}}, {{IPA|*qʰ-}} and {{IPA|*ɢ-}}, and similarly labio-uvular stops {{IPA|*qʷ-}}, {{IPA|*qʷʰ-}} and {{IPA|*ɢʷ-}} in place of {{IPA|*ʔʷ-}}, {{IPA|*hʷ-}} and {{IPA|*w-}}.{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|2000|pp=14–15}}{{sfnp|Sagart|2007}}

=== Evidence from Min Chinese ===
Modern [[Min dialects]], particularly those of northwest [[Fujian]], show reflexes of distinctions not reflected in Middle Chinese.
For example, the following dental initials have been identified in reconstructed [[proto-Min language|proto-Min]]:{{sfnp|Norman|1973|pp=227, 230, 233, 235}}{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=228–229}}
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center"
