| {{IPA|*Kʷ-}}             || {{IPA|*Kʷr-}}            || {{IPA|*Kʷrj-}}      ||      {{IPA|*Kʷj-}}     || {{IPA|*Kʷ-}}
|}

Here {{IPA|*P}}, {{IPA|*T}}, {{IPA|*TS}}, {{IPA|*K}} and {{IPA|*Kʷ}} stand for consonant classes in Old Chinese.
Columns III-3 and III-4 represent the ''[[chóngniǔ]]'' distinction among some syllables with division-III finals, which are placed in rows 3 or 4 of the Song dynasty [[rhyme table]]s.
The two are generally identical in modern Chinese varieties, but [[Sinoxenic]] forms often have a palatal element for III-4 but not III-3.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=63, 75–79, 282–287}}{{efn|The precise nature of the ''chóngniǔ'' distinction in Middle Chinese is disputed.  In their Middle Chinese reconstructions, Li and Baxter distinguish them by using ''-ji-'' as a purely notational device for III-4.{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|p=224}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=63}}}}

Baxter's account departs from the earlier reconstruction of Li Fang-Kuei in its treatment of {{IPA|*-j-}} and {{IPA|*-rj-}} after labial and guttural initials.
Li proposed {{IPA|*Krj-}} as the source of palatal initials occurring in phonetic series with velars or laryngeals, found no evidence for {{IPA|*Prj-}}, and attributed the ''chongniu'' distinction to the vowel.
Following proposals by Pulleyblank, Baxter explains ''chongniu'' using {{IPA|*-rj-}} and postulates that plain velars and laryngeals were palatalized when followed by both {{IPA|*-j-}} (but not {{IPA|*-rj-}}) and a front vowel.
However a significant number of palatalizations are not explained by this rule.{{sfnp|Handel|2003|p=555}}{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1962a|pp=98–107}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=210–214, 280}}

=== Type A and B syllables ===
A fundamental distinction within Middle Chinese is between syllables with division-III finals and the rest, labelled types B and A respectively by Pulleyblank.
Most scholars believe that type B syllables were characterized by a palatal medial ''-j-'' in Middle Chinese.
Although many authors have projected this medial back to a medial {{IPA|*-j-}} in Old Chinese, others have suggested that the Middle Chinese medial was a secondary development not present in Old Chinese.
Evidence includes the use of type B syllables to transcribe foreign words lacking any such medial, the lack of the medial in Tibeto-Burman cognates and modern Min reflexes, and the fact that it is ignored in phonetic series.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=287–290}}{{sfnp|Norman|1994|pp=400–402}}
Nonetheless, scholars agree that the difference reflects a real phonological distinction of some sort, often described noncommittally as a distinction between type A and B syllables using a variety of notations.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1977–1978|pp=183–185}}{{sfnp|Norman|1994|p=400}}{{sfnp|Schuessler|2007|p=95}}
The distinction has been variously ascribed to:
* the presence or absence of a prefix.  Jakhontov held that type B reflected a prefix {{IPA|*d-}},{{sfnp|Norman|1994|p=400}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=288}} while Ferlus suggested that type A arose from an unstressed prefix {{IPA|*Cə-}} (a [[minor syllable]]), which conditioned syllabic [[tenseness]] contrasting with laxness in type B syllables.{{sfnp|Ferlus|2001|pp=305–307}}
* a length distinction of the main vowel. Pulleyblank initially proposed that type B syllables had longer vowels,{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1992|p=379}} but Starostin and Zhengzhang later proposed long vowels for type A and short vowels for type B.{{sfnp|Handel|2003|p=550}}{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|1991|pp=160–161}}{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|2000|pp=48–57}}
* a [[prosodic]] distinction, as later proposed by Pulleyblank.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1992|p=379}}
* [[pharyngealization]] of the initial consonant.  [[Jerry Norman (sinologist)|Norman]] suggested that type B syllables (his class C), which comprised over half of the syllables of the ''Qieyun'', were in fact [[markedness|unmarked]] in Old Chinese.  Instead, he proposed that the remaining syllables were marked by retroflexion (the {{IPA|*-r-}} medial) or pharyngealization, either of which prevented palatalization in Middle Chinese.{{sfnp|Norman|1994}}  Baxter and [[Laurent Sagart|Sagart]] have adopted a variant of this proposal, reconstructing pharyngealized initials in all type A syllables.{{sfnp|Baxter|Sagart|2014|pp=43, 68–76}}

== Vowels ==

[[File:Gu yanwu.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A Qing dynasty scholar in traditional dress|[[Gu Yanwu]], who began the systematic study of ''[[Shijing]]'' rhymes]]
A reconstruction of Old Chinese finals must explain the rhyming practice of the ''[[Shijing]]'', a collection of songs and poetry from the 10th to 7th centuries BC.
Again some of these songs still rhyme in modern varieties of Chinese, but many do not.
This was attributed to lax rhyming practice until the late-[[Ming dynasty]] scholar [[Chen Di]] argued that a former consistency had been obscured by [[sound change]].{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=150–155}}{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=42}}
The systematic study of Old Chinese rhymes began in the 17th century, when [[Gu Yanwu]] divided the rhyming words of the ''Shijing'' into ten rhyme groups (''yùnbù'' {{lang|zh-Hant|韻部}}).{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=155–157}}
These groups were subsequently refined by other scholars, culminating in a standard set of 31 in the 1930s.
One of these scholars, [[Duan Yucai]], stated the important principle that characters in the same phonetic series would be in the same rhyme group,{{efn|{{lang|zh-Hant|同聲必同部}} ''Tóng shēng bì tóng bù''.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=831}}}} making it possible to assign almost all words to rhyme groups.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=157–170}}{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=43–44}}

Assuming that rhyming syllables had the same main vowel, Li Fang-Kuei proposed a system of four vowels {{IPA|*i}}, {{IPA|*u}}, {{IPA|*ə}} and {{IPA|*a}}.
He also included three diphthongs {{IPA|*iə}}, {{IPA|*ia}} and {{IPA|*ua}} to account for syllables that were placed in rhyme groups reconstructed with {{IPA|*ə}} or {{IPA|*a}} but were distinguished in Middle Chinese.{{sfnp|Li|1974–1975|pp=243–247}}
In the late 1980s, [[Zhengzhang Shangfang]], [[Sergei Starostin]] and William Baxter (following [[Nicholas Bodman]]) independently argued that these rhyme groups should be split, refining the 31 traditional rhyme groups into more than 50 groups corresponding to a six-vowel system.{{sfnp|Zhengzhang|2000|pp=42–43}}{{sfnp|Starostin|1989|pp=343–429}}{{sfnp|Bodman|1980|p=47}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=180, 253–254, 813}}{{sfnp|Baxter|2006}}
Baxter supported this thesis with a statistical analysis of the rhymes of the ''Shijing'', though there were too few rhymes with codas {{IPA|*-p}}, {{IPA|*-m}} and {{IPA|*-kʷ}} to produce statistically significant results.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=560–562}}

The following table illustrates these analyses, listing the names of the 31 traditional rhyme groups with their Middle Chinese reflexes and their postulated Old Chinese vowels in the systems of Li and Baxter.
Following the traditional analysis, the rhyme groups are organized into three parallel sets, depending on the corresponding type of coda in Middle Chinese.
For simplicity, only Middle Chinese finals of divisions I and IV are listed, as the complex vocalism of divisions II and III is believed to reflect the influence of Old Chinese medials {{IPA|*-r-}} and {{IPA|*-j-}} (see previous section).<ref>Tabulation of rhyme groups from {{harvp|Pulleyblank|1977–1978|p=181}} and {{harvp|Norman|1988|p=48}}.  Data from {{harvp|Baxter|1992|pp=141–150, 170, 243–246, 254–255, 298–302}} and {{harvp|Li|1974–1975|pp=252–279}}.</ref>{{efn|Each rhyme group was named after one of the corresponding ''Guangyun'' rhymes, with the choice sometimes varying between authors.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=141}}}}
