== Tones and final consonants ==
There has been much controversy over the relationship between final consonants and tones, and indeed whether Old Chinese lacked the tones characteristic of later periods, as first suggested by the [[Ming dynasty]] scholar [[Chen Di]].{{efn|{{zh|c=“四聲之辯，古人未有。”}} in Chen Di (1541–1617), ''Máo Shī Gǔ Yīn Kǎo'' {{lang|zh-Hant|《毛詩古音考》}}, quoted in {{harvp|Wang|1985|p=72}}.}}

The [[four tones (Middle Chinese)|four tones]] of Middle Chinese were first described by [[Shen Yue]] around AD 500.
They were the "level" ({{lang|zh-Hant|平}} ''píng''), "rising" ({{lang|zh-Hant|上}} ''shǎng''), "departing" ({{lang|zh-Hant|去}} ''qù''), and "[[checked tone|entering]]" ({{lang|zh-Hant|入}} ''rù'') tones, with the last category consisting of the syllables ending in stops (''-p'', ''-t'' or ''-k'').{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=303}}
Although rhymes in the ''Shijing'' usually respect these tone categories, there are many cases of characters that are now pronounced with different tones rhyming together in the songs, mostly between the departing and entering tones.
This led [[Duan Yucai]] to suggest that Old Chinese lacked the departing tone.
[[Wang Niansun]] (1744 - 1832) and  [[Jiang Yougao]] (d.1851) decided that the language had the same tones as Middle Chinese, but some words had later shifted between tones, a view that is still widely held among linguists in China.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=304–305}}{{sfnp|Wang|1985|pp=72–77}}

Karlgren also noted many cases where words in the departing and entering tones shared a phonetic element, e.g.
* {{lang|zh-Hant|賴}} ''lâi-'' 'depend on' and {{lang|zh-Hant|剌}} ''lât'' 'wicked'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 272e,a.</ref>
* {{lang|zh-Hant|欬}} ''khəi-'' 'cough' and {{lang|zh-Hant|刻}} ''khək'' 'cut; engrave'<ref>[[#{{harvid|Karlgren|1957}}|GSR]] 937s,v.</ref>
He suggested that the departing tone words in such pairs had ended with a final voiced stop ({{IPA|*-d}} or {{IPA|*-ɡ}}) in Old Chinese.{{sfnp|Karlgren|1923|pp=27–30}}
Being unwilling to split rhyme groups, Dong Tonghe and Li Fang-Kuei extended these final voiced stops to whole rhyme groups.
The only exceptions were the {{lang|zh-Hant|歌}} and {{lang|zh-Hant|祭}} groups (Li's {{IPA|*-ar}} and {{IPA|*-ad}}), in which the traditional analysis already distinguished the syllables with entering tone contacts.
The resulting scarcity of open syllables has been criticized on [[Linguistic typology|typological]] grounds.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=331–333}}
Wang Li preferred to reallocate words with connections to the entering tone to the corresponding entering tone group, proposing that the final stop was lost after a long vowel.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=340–342}}

Another perspective is provided by [[André-Georges Haudricourt|Haudricourt]]'s demonstration that the tones of [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], which have a very similar structure to those of Middle Chinese, were derived from earlier final consonants.
The Vietnamese counterparts of the rising and departing tones derived from a final glottal stop and {{IPA|*-s}} respectively, the latter developing to a glottal fricative {{IPA|*-h}}.
These glottal post-codas respectively conditioned rising and falling pitch contours, which became distinctive when the post-codas were lost.{{sfnp|Haudricourt|1954a}}
Haudricourt also suggested that the Chinese departing tone was reflected an Old Chinese derivational suffix {{IPA|*-s}}.
The connection with stop finals would then be explained as syllables ending with {{IPA|*-ts}} or {{IPA|*-ks}}, with the stops later disappearing, allowing rhymes with open syllables.{{sfnp|Haudricourt|1954b|pp=363–364}}
The absence of a corresponding labial final could be attributed to early [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]] of {{IPA|*-ps}} to {{IPA|*-ts}}.
Pulleyblank supported the theory with several examples of syllables in the departing tone being used to transcribe foreign words ending in ''-s'' into Chinese.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=308–317}}{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=54–57}}{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1962b|pp=216–225}}

Pulleyblank took Haudricourt's suggestion to its logical conclusion, proposing that the Chinese rising tone had also arisen from a final glottal stop.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1962b|pp=225–227}}
Mei Tsu-lin supported this theory with evidence from early transcriptions of Sanskrit words, and pointed out that rising tone words end in a glottal stop in some modern Chinese dialects, e.g. [[Wenzhounese]] and some Min dialects.{{sfnp|Mei|1970}}
In addition, most of the entering tone words that rhyme with rising tone words in the ''Shijing'' end in ''-k''.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=322}}

Together, these hypotheses lead to the following set of Old Chinese syllable codas:{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=181–183}}
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;"
